  <tagline><![CDATA[For many, Sirmione in the leads the race for Lake Garda’s prettiest town, with a storybook medieval castle and lake views all around; perfect for lakeside walking in the summer]]></tagline>
  <thingsToDo><![CDATA[<h3>History and culture in Sirmione</h3>
<p>Sirmione town has a rich history so there’s lots to explore and learn. The Grotte di Catullo are fascinating Roman ruins at the tip of the peninsula and the ancient Scaligero Castle, which was built during the La Scala family dynasty is a fantastic historic site to behold. Sirmione’s been known for its healing thermal waters since the Roman times and there’s plenty of places to enjoy them on the tiny peninsula. Aquaria’s our go-to place when we need to relax - it has the biggest pools and over 10,000 square metres to chill out in.</p>
<h3>Exploring further afield: hopping from town to town on Lake Garda and discovering Verona</h3>
<p>It’s easy to get to other resorts on the lake as ferries run all day from the central port. Head over to <a data-udi="umb://document/89a5238595c34e53a5ef4c989b459fce" href="/{localLink:umb://document/89a5238595c34e53a5ef4c989b459fce}" title="Malcesine">Malcesine</a> where you can take the cable car up to Monte Baldo and explore a fantastic walking area with panoramic views of the lake and surrounding mountains. If you're looking for some really challenging uphill ascents, then Limone's the town to go to- there are no cable cars here, so getting up to the top of the mountain requires mountain goat abilities!</p>
<p>If culture is what you're looking for, or you're a literary fanatic, them jump on the bus, and you can be in <a data-udi="umb://document/41229767036d47f28a27ac846e23458b" href="/{localLink:umb://document/41229767036d47f28a27ac846e23458b}" title="Verona">Verona</a> in under an hour. Verona's a fantastic city to walk around– its main attractions are all within walking distance, so it's easy to see all the sights in one day; cross the Ponte Pietra and walk up to the Piazzale Castel San Pietro for stunning views of the city.</p>
<h3>Savouring food &amp; wine on Lake Grrda</h3>
<p>You can't leave Sirmione without testing out the ever popular gelato. There are plenty of gelaterie in the pedestrianised centre, so pick out your favourite flavour (or two, or three) and savour it as you wander along the lakeside promenade in the summer sunshine. When it's time for lunch or dinner, walk over to Piazza Carducci where you'll be spoilt for choice for restaurants and cafés.</p>]]></thingsToDo>
